of town, because I can stand the heat.</i>

450
00:40:10,432 --> 00:40:13,302
<i>We were splittin' because
things were going all wrong.</i>

451
00:40:13,685 --> 00:40:16,934
<i>Nadine's hex was a little more
powerful than I had calculated.</i>

452
00:40:18,439 --> 00:40:22,567
<i>It was time to change the scenery, which
happened when you went crossroading.</i>

453
00:40:22,693 --> 00:40:25,777
<i>Dianne got the narcotics together
and sent them ahead by bus</i>

454
00:40:25,904 --> 00:40:28,276
<i>to depots across the
Pacific Northwest</i>

455
00:40:28,406 --> 00:40:31,941
<i>so we could rendezvous with
the drugs as we needed them.</i>

456
00:40:32,118 --> 00:40:35,368
<i>We couldn't afford to be caught
with a car full of narcotics,</i>

457
00:40:35,496 --> 00:40:39,707
<i>so we had a backup plan in the form of a
hole punched in the floorboard of our car.</i>

458
00:40:41,377 --> 00:40:46,085
<i>When the flashing red lights became a
reality, down the hole went the stash.</i>

459
00:40:46,214 --> 00:40:48,171
Is something the matter, Officer?

460
00:40:48,633 --> 00:40:50,673
<i>Then we'd go to the next rendezvous,</i>

461
00:40:50,802 --> 00:40:55,131
<i>which was hopefully within eight
hours, before the drugs wore off.</i>

462
00:40:55,264 --> 00:41:00,471
<i>No construction stiff workin' overtime
takes more stress and strain than we did,</i>

463
00:41:00,603 --> 00:41:02,761
<i>just trying to stay high.</i>

464
00:42:01,409 --> 00:42:05,406
We rented this truck not necessarily
because we need another vehicle.

465
00:42:05,538 --> 00:42:07,779
But we can move easier
in a vehicle like this.

466
00:42:07,915 --> 00:42:11,283
It's got the right licence plates
so the average Joe will just think

467
00:42:11,418 --> 00:42:15,581
we're a couple farm boys and a prostitute
in town for a little joyride.

468
00:42:15,714 --> 00:42:16,709
Hey!

469
00:42:16,840 --> 00:42:19,128
I always wanted to be a farmer, Bob.

470
00:42:26,765 --> 00:42:29,435
Whoa. Did you guys see that?

471
00:42:30,727 --> 00:42:33,432
- What?
- The transom.

472
00:42:33,563 --> 00:42:36,434
You guys didn't see the open transom?

473
00:42:36,566 --> 00:42:39,318
- No.
- What's a transom, Bob?

474
00:42:42,530 --> 00:42:45,199
It's all clear in the back.

475
00:42:46,409 --> 00:42:49,694
All right. Gimme a lift,
then meet me around back.

476
00:42:50,621 --> 00:42:53,290
Ready? One, two, three.

477
00:43:18,730 --> 00:43:21,600
Nadine, take these and
put it inside the truck.

478
00:43:21,733 --> 00:43:26,774
Rick, step in here. I want you to look at
these two safes. See them over there?

479
00:43:43,211 --> 00:43:45,250
Rick. Let's go.

480
00:43:51,510 --> 00:43:53,550
Shut up!

481
00:43:57,182 --> 00:44:00,717
Christ! You're finished,
hopheads. You blew it.

482
00:44:11,153 --> 00:44:14,071
Hey, babe, you playin'
cards? Who's winning?

483
00:44:14,198 --> 00:44:16,107
<i>What's the matter with her?</i>

484
00:44:16,325 --> 00:44:18,364
Nothin'.

485
00:44:18,994 --> 00:44:21,033
Cocaine.

486
00:44:25,500 --> 00:44:28,833
- Holy shit.
- What is it, Bob?

487
00:44:29,420 --> 00:44:31,745
Powdered Dilaudid, that's what.

488
00:44:31,881 --> 00:44:36,258
A whole, untouched one-eighth
ounce bottle of powdered D.

489
00:44:36,385 --> 00:44:38,128
Whoo!

490
00:44:38,262 --> 00:44:42,508
Should be another partially
filled one in here somewhere.

491
00:44:43,934 --> 00:44:45,973
You see it?

492
00:44:47,478 --> 00:44:51,262
Rick, do you have any idea
what this little bottle is worth?

493
00:44:51,399 --> 00:44:56,440
- No, Bob. What's it worth?
- This here little bottle...

494
00:44:56,570 --> 00:44:58,610
has got 840-some-odd sixteenths.

495
00:44:58,739 --> 00:45:03,235
And at ten dollars a sixteenth,
that comes to around 8,400 dollars

496
00:45:03,452 --> 00:45:07,235
of the best goddamn
pharmaceutical dope money can buy.

497
00:45:07,414 --> 00:45:12,752
What a find. This here little bottle
ought to last the three of us a week.

498
00:45:13,336 --> 00:45:16,206
I'd better take that.

499
00:45:16,338 --> 00:45:18,912
Guess we must've outrun
that hex we had on us, eh, Bob?

500
00:45:19,967 --> 00:45:24,593
- Sure glad we started crossroading.
- Bob? Let's shoot it.

501
00:45:24,846 --> 00:45:28,215
You gotta be careful with
this stuff. It can kill you.

502
00:45:29,392 --> 00:45:31,349
Dianne, get a glass of water.

503
00:45:36,565 --> 00:45:38,605
Do it slow.

504
00:45:43,780 --> 00:45:46,698
I'll show you how we're
gonna hide this stuff.

505
00:45:53,039 --> 00:45:55,078
Right up here.

506
00:46:14,017 --> 00:46:16,638
Now, we'll take this stuff

507
00:46:16,769 --> 00:46:20,054
and then we'll cross over
a couple of these units

508
00:46:20,940 --> 00:46:23,609
and stash it over somebody else's room.

509
00:46:38,914 --> 00:46:39,910
Wow.

510
00:46:50,008 --> 00:46:51,632
Hey.

511
00:46:52,010 --> 00:46:54,049
Hey.

512
00:46:55,722 --> 00:46:57,761
Come on. Buck up.

513
00:46:58,599 --> 00:47:01,055
So you blew it. Big deal.

514
00:47:01,644 --> 00:47:06,186
Listen, we're gonna go out for a couple of
hours, but we'll be back in a little bit.

515
00:47:08,567 --> 00:47:11,140
What'd that son of a bitch say about me?

516
00:47:11,278 --> 00:47:13,317
He didn't say anything about you.

517
00:47:13,446 --> 00:47:16,281
Yeah, but he's not gonna
take me along any more, is he?

518
00:47:16,407 --> 00:47:22,243
Then one day you'll all just drop me off
somewhere and you'll never come back.

519
00:47:25,124 --> 00:47:27,793
Nadine, what are you talkin' about?

520
00:47:28,961 --> 00:47:32,792
Come on, honey. You're with me.
I'm not gonna leave you anywhere.

521
00:47:33,882 --> 00:47:35,708
He is a goddamn...

522
00:47:35,842 --> 00:47:36,957
- Shut up!
...hog!

523
00:47:37,135 --> 00:47:39,293
- Hog! Hog!
- Hey, shut up. Come on, honey.

524
00:47:39,429 --> 00:47:43,473
- Hog!
- Don't do that. Please, Nadine.

525
00:47:44,850 --> 00:47:47,519
We got a good thing goin' here.

526
00:47:48,062 --> 00:47:50,731
Why do you want to rock the boat?

527
00:47:51,064 --> 00:47:53,733
I just can't stand their superior ways.

528
00:47:54,568 --> 00:47:59,644
And all that crap about hexes.
You don't believe that stuff, do you?

529
00:47:59,781 --> 00:48:02,188
Look, Nadine, I don't know. OK?

530
00:48:02,325 --> 00:48:07,117
I mean, all we have to do is not talk about
pets and not leave any hats on any beds.

531
00:48:07,246 --> 00:48:09,867
Now, what's hard about that?

532
00:48:09,998 --> 00:48:16,250
I'm just gonna prove to all of you that
a hat on a bed doesn't mean anything.

533
00:48:18,214 --> 00:48:20,456
Hey, Rick. Let's go. Come on.

534
00:48:20,592 --> 00:48:23,261
I really wish you hadn't done that.

535
00:48:32,436 --> 00:48:37,856
You're just goin' out with them tonight.
When you come back, I'll show all of you.

536
00:48:37,983 --> 00:48:41,766
When I come back, I don't want to see
that hat on the bed. All right, honey?

537
00:48:44,572 --> 00:48:48,819
You know, Nadine, there's just
no talking to you sometimes. Fuck.

538
00:48:59,210 --> 00:49:01,666
Hey, Rick. Rick. Rick.

539
00:49:02,880 --> 00:49:07,044
Don't be too aggressive, man. We're
just trying to create a diversion. OK?

540
00:49:07,176 --> 00:49:10,093
- I don't want anybody gettin' hurt.
- OK, Bob.

541
00:49:14,850 --> 00:49:17,519
- OK, babe, you all set?
- Yeah.

542
00:49:57,848 --> 00:49:59,306
Prepare to die.

543
00:51:05,243 --> 00:51:06,785
Demerol. Shit.

544
00:51:26,012 --> 00:51:27,423
Argh!

545
00:51:43,654 --> 00:51:46,323
This just isn't like him.

546
00:51:46,448 --> 00:51:49,947
Bob is like a rabbit.
In and out, and no nonsense.

547
00:51:51,494 --> 00:51:54,614
That goes for a lot more
than a hospital pharmacy.

548
00:52:16,601 --> 00:52:21,595
<i>Mrs Robb to Admitting.
Mrs Jane Robb to Admitting.</i>

549
00:52:32,198 --> 00:52:34,072
Fuck!

550
00:53:18,991 --> 00:53:22,194
I don't think he's gonna come.
Why don't we go back?

551
00:53:24,538 --> 00:53:26,495
They got him.

552
00:53:26,624 --> 00:53:29,909
Bastards got him. I know it.

553
00:53:30,043 --> 00:53:32,795
I can feel it in my heart.

554
00:53:32,921 --> 00:53:34,960
Dirty bastards.

555
00:53:42,555 --> 00:53:44,594
Nadine.

556
00:54:06,118 --> 00:54:08,158
Oh, my God.

557
00:54:10,831 --> 00:54:13,203
Honey? I'm home.

558
00:54:18,880 --> 00:54:22,877
You're not gonna believe the shit
that happened to me tonight.

559
00:54:23,801 --> 00:54:25,877
What's goin' on?

560
00:54:26,012 --> 00:54:28,051
Who put the goddamn hat on the bed?

561
00:54:28,681 --> 00:54:30,803
She did, Bob.

562
00:54:30,933 --> 00:54:33,340
She didn't mean anything by it.

563
00:54:44,570 --> 00:54:46,610
She bit it.

564
00:54:51,160 --> 00:54:55,453
Where'd she get the stuff? She couldn't
have done this on no two sixteenths.

565
00:54:55,580 --> 00:54:58,250
What's she been doing? Saving it up?

566
00:55:05,006 --> 00:55:08,624
- Who gave her this?
- What is it?

567
00:55:08,759 --> 00:55:12,045
Damn! She must've picked it up
off the floor of the truck

568
00:55:12,179 --> 00:55:14,931
when we were collecting these bottles.

569
00:55:16,767 --> 00:55:18,806
Conniving little bitch.

570
00:55:19,978 --> 00:55:22,017
Bob?

571
00:55:22,605 --> 00:55:26,685
You can't say that
about her, Bob. She's dead.

572
00:55:28,277 --> 00:55:30,946
You don't say anything bad about her.

573
00:55:34,825 --> 00:55:36,864
Rick.

574
00:55:38,662 --> 00:55:40,701
She beat you.

575
00:55:41,331 --> 00:55:46,158
Your own woman beat you
out of your cut on a score.

576
00:55:49,130 --> 00:55:51,585
She got what she deserves.

577
00:55:53,759 --> 00:55:55,218
Listen, man.

578
00:55:55,344 --> 00:55:59,673
Not only that. She threw a hex on us
we'll all be lucky to outrun, huh?

579
00:56:01,391 --> 00:56:06,100
She left us with an OD'd stiff, which is
paramount to a murder beef in this state.

580
00:56:06,229 --> 00:56:09,514
For Christ's sake, get this
goddamn hat off the bed!

581
00:56:31,127 --> 00:56:32,621
Cold.

582
00:57:10,330 --> 00:57:13,330
Hell, it's like trying
to raise a couple of kids

583
00:57:13,458 --> 00:57:17,537
when you take on a couple like that
and try and teach 'em to steal.

584
00:57:18,754 --> 00:57:20,414
Know what I mean, Dianne?

585
00:57:22,341 --> 00:57:24,380
All these kids.

586
00:57:25,427 --> 00:57:27,466
They're all TV babies.

587
00:57:28,138 --> 00:57:32,467
They've been watching people killin'
each other on the boob tube for so long,

588
00:57:32,600 --> 00:57:34,640
it's all they know.

589
00:57:35,436 --> 00:57:38,971
Hell, they think it's legal. They
think it's the right thing to do.

590
00:57:39,106 --> 00:57:41,514
I know, hon.

591
00:57:46,363 --> 00:57:48,770
I'm gettin' real tired.

592
00:57:51,785 --> 00:57:53,444
Poor Nadine.

593
00:57:54,912 --> 00:57:57,783
She was just a goddamn kid.

594
00:58:01,544 --> 00:58:03,583
Now what?

595
00:58:06,923 --> 00:58:10,339
- Hello. Are you Mr Hughes?
- Yeah.

596
00:58:10,468 --> 00:58:14,051
- Are you planning to check out today?
- No. Why?

597
00:58:14,180 --> 00:58:16,801
Well, you see, sir,
we have prior commitments

598
00:58:16,933 --> 00:58:21,013
in the form of a reservation
for your room today.

599
00:58:22,396 --> 00:58:24,685
Today?

600
00:58:24,815 --> 00:58:27,388
- You mean check out today?
- I'm afraid so.

601
00:58:27,526 --> 00:58:31,025
You see, we're having
a sheriffs' convention in town

602
00:58:31,154 --> 00:58:35,615
and all these rooms have been reserved
in advance for them 90 days ago.

603
00:58:40,246 --> 00:58:44,195
All right. Could I go down to the office
and talk to you in about ten minutes?

604
00:58:44,333 --> 00:58:46,372
Give me ten minutes.

605
00:58:51,840 --> 00:58:54,591
We're gonna know
some of these guys, I'll bet.

606
00:58:54,718 --> 00:58:57,718
I don't believe it.
I don't fuckin' believe it.

607
00:58:58,388 --> 00:59:01,139
A sheriffs' convention, no less.

608
00:59:01,265 --> 00:59:04,551
Why couldn't it have been
a Tupperware convention?

609
00:59:05,227 --> 00:59:07,683
Or better yet, an undertakers'.

610
00:59:22,410 --> 00:59:24,449
Excuse me.

611
00:59:31,835 --> 00:59:34,041
Hello?

612
00:59:34,171 --> 00:59:36,210
Anything?

613
00:59:36,673 --> 00:59:41,749
Sorry, Mr Hughes. You should have let us
know you intended on staying this long.

614
00:59:43,012 --> 00:59:49,097
Look, I've got a colleague in that room
and he's sick with the mumps.

615
00:59:49,810 --> 00:59:53,143
I'm afraid to move him. I mean,
what if they should spread?

616
00:59:53,271 --> 00:59:57,399
The doc said all we need is another day.
He can travel in another day. Come on.

617
00:59:58,151 --> 00:59:59,894
Come on.

618
01:00:39,648 --> 01:00:42,317
<i>Lock him up.
He did it. Lock him up!</i>

619
01:00:42,442 --> 01:00:44,897
<i>Guilty! Guilty!</i>

620
01:00:48,698 --> 01:00:53,489
It's gonna be one heck of a time
getting her out of that crawlspace.

621
01:00:56,204 --> 01:00:59,787
Don't know if I'm ever gonna
get my nails done now.

622
01:01:03,670 --> 01:01:06,457
Nadine really got to you, didn't she, Bob?

623
01:01:07,465 --> 01:01:10,134
Yeah, well, I'll tell you what's wrong.

624
01:01:10,259 --> 01:01:14,257
I'm afraid some big fat cop's gonna come
rumbling through this door any minute.

625
01:01:14,388 --> 01:01:17,223
He'll say "Get outta this room.
This is my room."

626
01:01:22,562 --> 01:01:24,601
Dianne.

627
01:01:25,607 --> 01:01:27,646
Yeah?

628
01:01:28,484 --> 01:01:30,227
I love you.

629
01:01:33,072 --> 01:01:35,527
I love you, too.

630
01:01:49,212 --> 01:01:51,881
- Hey, Dianne?
- Hm?

631
01:01:55,926 --> 01:01:59,046
We have that blue garment bag?
The big one.

632
01:02:40,676 --> 01:02:42,715
Dianne?

633
01:03:01,820 --> 01:03:06,398
Don't worry, Bob. We'll make it.
We always do, don't we?

634
01:03:28,470 --> 01:03:31,755
Honey? Let's go, dear.
We're gonna miss our flight.

635
01:03:32,849 --> 01:03:34,888
Hi.

636
01:03:38,729 --> 01:03:40,769
Wow.

637
01:03:41,857 --> 01:03:44,313
What a busy day.

638
01:03:46,528 --> 01:03:48,402
What do you say we go up to the attic,

639
01:03:48,530 --> 01:03:52,314
divide the stuff up with Rick
and give him the big end?

640
01:03:52,450 --> 01:03:54,775
Don't count him short.

641
01:03:54,911 --> 01:03:58,114
What's going on, Bob?
What are you thinking about?

642
01:04:02,001 --> 01:04:04,040
Nothin'.

643
01:04:07,589 --> 01:04:12,417
I'm thinking about, uh...
headin' back home.

644
01:04:14,053 --> 01:04:16,342
Gettin' in the 21-day
methadone programme.

645
01:04:16,681 --> 01:04:20,014
- Cleaning up my act.
- Are you kidding?

646
01:04:21,143 --> 01:04:23,266
No, I'm not.

647
01:04:25,981 --> 01:04:27,938
Dianne,

648
01:04:28,984 --> 01:04:31,439
I can't do it any more.

649
01:04:32,737 --> 01:04:35,228
I'm not goin' on
no withdrawal programme.

650
01:04:35,365 --> 01:04:37,820
So what's gonna happen to me?

651
01:04:38,701 --> 01:04:41,157
Why don't you come with me?

652
01:04:41,746 --> 01:04:46,288
No, thanks, buster. Not a fucking word
do you mention about all this.

653
01:04:46,875 --> 01:04:51,204
Right out of the clear blue sky you say
you're gonna clean up your hand.

654
01:04:51,338 --> 01:04:53,579
And you know I can't.

655
01:04:56,843 --> 01:04:59,168
Look, Dianne, do what you want.

656
01:04:59,303 --> 01:05:02,755
Take whatever we got. I only
need enough to get me home.

657
01:05:23,367 --> 01:05:26,238
Get the shovel. I'll take care of her.

658
01:05:39,340 --> 01:05:41,796
Go back to the truck.

659
01:05:52,144 --> 01:05:54,183
Go.

660
01:11:10,604 --> 01:11:14,601
<i>Have you ever been on
a withdrawal programme before?</i>

661
01:11:14,733 --> 01:11:16,061
<i>No.</i>

662
01:11:16,192 --> 01:11:20,735
<i>I see. How long have
you been on drugs altogether?</i>

663
01:11:23,908 --> 01:11:25,367
<i>All my life.</i>

664
01:11:26,452 --> 01:11:29,322
<i>Then this isn't
your first time withdrawing?</i>

665
01:11:29,455 --> 01:11:34,163
<i>No. This is my first time
withdrawing on methadone.</i>

666
01:11:35,502 --> 01:11:37,708
<i>How old are you now?</i>

667
01:11:37,837 --> 01:11:39,877
<i>26.</i>

668
01:11:40,340 --> 01:11:43,673
<i>- Are you married?
- Uh, yeah.</i>

669
01:11:45,011 --> 01:11:46,553
Where is your wife?

670
01:11:46,679 --> 01:11:48,755
I don't know.

671
01:11:48,889 --> 01:11:50,264
Do you have children?

672
01:11:50,391 --> 01:11:52,430
No.

673
01:11:52,893 --> 01:11:54,850
Um...

674
01:11:54,978 --> 01:11:57,101
Do you have a job?

675
01:11:57,230 --> 01:11:59,270
No.

676
01:11:59,733 --> 01:12:02,686
Do you have a Social Security number?

677
01:12:03,736 --> 01:12:05,776
No.

678
01:12:07,156 --> 01:12:10,026
Have you ever been
convicted of a felony?

679
01:12:12,369 --> 01:12:16,153
- Yeah, a few times.
- What were they?

680
01:12:16,748 --> 01:12:19,417
What felonies were you convicted of?

681
01:12:20,251 --> 01:12:22,493
What do you want? My life story?

682
01:12:23,880 --> 01:12:25,374
Look, lady.

683
01:12:25,673 --> 01:12:31,960
I'm a junkie. I like drugs. I like the whole lifestyle.
But it just didn't pay off.

684
01:12:35,307 --> 01:12:38,059
You know, you don't see
my kind of people.

685
01:12:38,977 --> 01:12:42,512
Cos my kind of people, they don't
come down here and beg dope.

686
01:12:42,647 --> 01:12:46,347
They go out and get it, and
if they miss, they go to jail

687
01:12:46,484 --> 01:12:50,778
and they kick alone with nothing
in some holding tank.

688
01:12:52,114 --> 01:12:53,941
I'm sorry, Bob.

689
01:12:54,074 --> 01:12:56,281
I don't mean to hassle you.

690
01:12:56,410 --> 01:13:01,285
All this is required. I'm sorry
if you think it's unnecessary.

691
01:13:02,916 --> 01:13:06,000
Have you ever considered
becoming a counsellor

692
01:13:06,127 --> 01:13:09,294
and helping other addicts
with their problems?

693
01:13:09,422 --> 01:13:10,999
No.

694
01:13:11,132 --> 01:13:13,254
Why not?

695
01:13:13,384 --> 01:13:16,420
Well, to begin with,

696
01:13:16,553 --> 01:13:22,591
nobody - and I mean nobody -
can talk a junkie out of using.

697
01:13:23,268 --> 01:13:28,095
You can talk to them for years, but sooner
or later they'll get ahold of something.

698
01:13:28,231 --> 01:13:31,813
Maybe it's not dope. Maybe it's booze.

699
01:13:31,943 --> 01:13:34,612
Maybe it's glue. Maybe it's gasoline.

700
01:13:35,613 --> 01:13:37,938
Maybe it's a gunshot in the head.

701
01:13:39,241 --> 01:13:41,068
But something.

702
01:13:41,201 --> 01:13:44,285
Something to relieve the pressures
of their everyday life,

703
01:13:44,412 --> 01:13:47,082
like... having to tie their shoes.

704
01:14:03,263 --> 01:14:05,718
Tom, you got some mail here.

705
01:14:08,268 --> 01:14:11,304
- Bless you.
- You're welcome.

706
01:14:26,660 --> 01:14:28,699
Father Murphy.

707
01:14:29,662 --> 01:14:31,702
Hey, Tom.

708
01:14:34,625 --> 01:14:36,867
Well, well.

709
01:14:37,545 --> 01:14:39,584
Bad Bobby Hughes.

710
01:14:40,714 --> 01:14:45,791
Imagine seeing you here
after all these years.

711
01:14:47,179 --> 01:14:48,922
You live here too?

712
01:14:49,055 --> 01:14:51,724
I have nowhere else to go.

713
01:14:52,976 --> 01:14:58,314
There is no demand in the priesthood
for elderly drug addicts.

714
01:14:58,439 --> 01:15:04,144
An indiscretion in 1970-
you were inside, I believe...

715
01:15:04,486 --> 01:15:08,234
resulted in my descent to this sorry state.

716
01:15:11,618 --> 01:15:15,911
As a matter of fact,
I'm feeling a bit sick right now.

717
01:15:16,956 --> 01:15:19,411
Are you holding?

718
01:15:20,084 --> 01:15:21,708
Nope.

719
01:15:21,835 --> 01:15:25,750
They got me on this
21-day thing. Methadone.

720
01:15:28,091 --> 01:15:30,131
What about yourself?

721
01:15:30,719 --> 01:15:32,592
Oh, sure.

722
01:15:32,846 --> 01:15:35,087
I'm on the programme.

723
01:15:35,223 --> 01:15:40,561
But sometimes I get a little bit ahead
of my schedule. You understand?

724
01:15:42,605 --> 01:15:50,398
And sometimes I think some junkie nurse
may be stepping on my medication.

725
01:15:51,863 --> 01:15:54,319
But I can't be sure.

726
01:15:56,075 --> 01:15:58,613
How about it? You wanna score?

727
01:15:58,744 --> 01:16:00,571
Nah.

728
01:16:01,872 --> 01:16:04,494
But I'll keep you company.

729
01:16:06,543 --> 01:16:09,081
This here is an art work.

730
01:16:09,212 --> 01:16:11,668
A work of art. So is that.

731
01:16:13,425 --> 01:16:15,464
More art work.

732
01:16:15,927 --> 01:16:18,596
Look at the bole on that tree there.

733
01:16:20,806 --> 01:16:24,970
That reminds me. I used
to know an old croaker.

734
01:16:25,102 --> 01:16:29,100
I think it was on that street.
Maybe it was the next street over.

735
01:16:29,231 --> 01:16:32,647
Ah... he'd write like a major.

736
01:16:33,485 --> 01:16:36,936
<i>Tom knew his way
around the old neighbourhoods.</i>

737
01:16:37,822 --> 01:16:39,779
<i>I'd known Tom since I
was an altar boy.</i>

738
01:16:39,907 --> 01:16:44,450
<i>Benevolent Father Murphy, the most
notorious dope fiend on the Coast.</i>

739
01:16:44,704 --> 01:16:49,614
<i>When he was holding he'd always share with
those who weren't. He was very kind.</i>

740
01:16:49,750 --> 01:16:54,625
<i>Tom was king then. He had it all.
His ass was covered in this life and the next.</i>

741
01:16:55,297 --> 01:16:58,167
<i>I bet he shot a million
bucks in his arm.</i>

742
01:17:00,927 --> 01:17:04,046
OK. This is what you call
a radial-arm drill press.

743
01:17:04,972 --> 01:17:08,507
Get the drill you want,
putting it in the holder.

744
01:17:08,642 --> 01:17:10,967
Make sure you've got a good grip on it.

745
01:17:11,186 --> 01:17:15,231
That brings your drill down to
your work. Position it over the hole.

746
01:17:15,357 --> 01:17:18,311
That's your clutch.
This is your power feed.

747
01:17:18,443 --> 01:17:21,194
This is the clutch that
engages the power feed.

748
01:17:21,321 --> 01:17:23,990
Put that in and just let it drill.

749
01:17:50,514 --> 01:17:52,637
<i>You go to work loaded, it'll show.</i>

750
01:17:52,808 --> 01:17:55,133
Being loaded's like being drunk.

751
01:17:55,269 --> 01:17:58,803
You drink or get high in the morning,
your boss is gonna see it.

752
01:17:58,939 --> 01:18:01,429
You'll get fired, then
you're not making money.

753
01:18:01,566 --> 01:18:03,973
Then you're gonna have
to do something else.

754
01:18:04,110 --> 01:18:07,111
You're gonna have to rob,
steal, sell. You know?

755
01:18:07,238 --> 01:18:08,946
Um...

756
01:18:09,073 --> 01:18:13,865
Somewhere in that robbing you might
end up killing your best buddy over a fix.

757
01:18:13,994 --> 01:18:17,114
You'll go down the tubes.
There's no other way around it.

758
01:18:17,247 --> 01:18:20,450
The more you use, the longer
you use, the further down you go.

759
01:18:21,418 --> 01:18:23,955
Then you're gonna find
you're on the bottom.

760
01:18:45,273 --> 01:18:47,846
Catching up on your reading?

761
01:18:51,737 --> 01:18:55,438
You didn't stay gone long,
Bob. What happened?

762
01:18:55,574 --> 01:18:57,613
Nothing happened.

763
01:18:58,076 --> 01:19:00,365
I hear you're on a methadone programme.

764
01:19:00,495 --> 01:19:05,038
You don't think that'll keep Trousinski
from jumping your ass, do you?

765
01:19:05,542 --> 01:19:08,377
To tell you the truth,
I haven't given it much thought.

766
01:19:09,837 --> 01:19:12,957
You know, for once
I'm not here to hassle you.

767
01:19:13,090 --> 01:19:17,668
Trousinski lost his gold badge over
that little incident. He's working traffic.

768
01:19:17,803 --> 01:19:21,337
He's made so many goddamn threats,
he's almost gonna have to hurt you.

769
01:19:21,473 --> 01:19:24,142
And I don't wanna see that happen.

770
01:19:25,060 --> 01:19:27,977
Man, look. What can I say?
I got a job, you know?

771
01:19:30,481 --> 01:19:34,313
What happened out there in the sticks,
Bob? Where's Dianne?

772
01:19:36,612 --> 01:19:39,281
You know how whimsical women are.

773
01:19:40,324 --> 01:19:45,199
She found some other dude to chase after
and off she went, chasin' after him.

774
01:19:46,913 --> 01:19:49,321
I find that a little hard to believe.

775
01:19:49,624 --> 01:19:54,582
You and Dianne have been running
around together since you were little kids.

776
01:20:00,926 --> 01:20:03,595
I hope you make out on that job of yours.

777
01:20:03,720 --> 01:20:07,338
And I sincerely hope that
you straighten up a little bit.

778
01:20:08,099 --> 01:20:09,759
Take care of yourself, Bob.

779
01:20:50,722 --> 01:20:53,295
My old lady's still
out there right now.

780
01:20:53,975 --> 01:20:56,726
Yeah. I can't do nothing with her. I tried.

781
01:20:56,853 --> 01:21:01,680
I told her to come. She won't come
cos she's doing her own thing.

782
01:21:01,815 --> 01:21:04,650
What I was doin', I was
goin' right to the source.

783
01:21:05,319 --> 01:21:09,482
Right to the source. Where do they
make drugs? In the drugstores.

784
01:21:12,283 --> 01:21:15,035
If you want some money
you go to the bank, huh?

785
01:21:17,455 --> 01:21:22,662
"Yeah, honey, I gotta stop by the bank and
the drugstore. I'll be home after a while."

786
01:21:23,836 --> 01:21:27,750
What are you crying for? You want
to do the drugs, you gotta pay for 'em.

787
01:21:27,881 --> 01:21:30,337
Where's my fuckin' money, you bitch?

788
01:21:32,677 --> 01:21:35,168
Punk. Where the fuck's my money?

789
01:21:35,305 --> 01:21:37,795
Come on. This is the third
time I had to ask you.

790
01:21:37,932 --> 01:21:41,716
What are you gonna say? Say something.
You want me to beat you more?

791
01:21:41,852 --> 01:21:45,435
Hey, David. What do you
think you're doin', man?

792
01:21:45,564 --> 01:21:47,722
Huh? What do you think you're doin'?

793
01:21:47,858 --> 01:21:50,349
This kid's cryin', man.

794
01:21:50,485 --> 01:21:52,691
So? It's business. What do you care?

795
01:21:52,821 --> 01:21:56,486
Why don't you go away and mind
your own business? What do you care?

796
01:21:56,616 --> 01:21:58,158
Cos it bugs me.

797
01:21:58,284 --> 01:22:00,775
- Take a walk.
- Hey, man. Come on.

798
01:22:00,912 --> 01:22:02,904
Goddamn!

799
01:22:03,039 --> 01:22:06,822
<i>- David, why don't you grow up, man?
- I am grown-up.</i>

800
01:22:06,959 --> 01:22:08,785
Asshole!

801
01:22:09,628 --> 01:22:11,834
Why didn't you do something, man?

802
01:22:11,963 --> 01:22:16,791
What's up with you, man? I thought you...
Man, I'm not buying you no lunch.

803
01:22:20,054 --> 01:22:23,423
You know, Tom, you told me
a lot of the old-time stories

804
01:22:23,557 --> 01:22:30,769
about how you used to stick your arm
in between the bars of the cell

805
01:22:31,106 --> 01:22:34,391
and a guard would come by and
he'd fire you up a shot of morphine.

806
01:22:34,526 --> 01:22:36,565
They never did that for me.

807
01:22:37,404 --> 01:22:40,073
They don't do that for anyone any more.

808
01:22:42,158 --> 01:22:50,450
Narcotics have been systematically
scapegoated and demonised.

809
01:22:52,542 --> 01:22:57,785
The idea that anyone can use drugs
and escape a horrible fate

810
01:22:57,922 --> 01:23:00,247
is anathema to these idiots.

811
01:23:01,509 --> 01:23:04,960
I predict in the near future

812
01:23:05,096 --> 01:23:09,757
right-wingers will use drug hysteria

813
01:23:10,476 --> 01:23:12,515
as a pretext

814
01:23:13,228 --> 01:23:18,269
to set up an international
police apparatus.

815
01:23:21,027 --> 01:23:28,025
I'm an old man and I may not live to see
a final solution of the drug problem.

816
01:23:30,869 --> 01:23:35,330
You know what, Tom? You might
have missed your calling.

817
01:23:35,624 --> 01:23:37,912
You should have been a philosopher.

818
01:23:38,043 --> 01:23:41,957
Well, Bob, in another life,
perhaps. In another life.

819
01:24:07,695 --> 01:24:09,734
Who is it?

820
01:24:10,531 --> 01:24:12,570
Who is it?

821
01:24:23,752 --> 01:24:25,329
Hey.

822
01:24:28,506 --> 01:24:31,590
Jesus. What kind of a dump is this?

823
01:24:33,093 --> 01:24:36,178
And where is the female?
You might as well trot her out.

824
01:24:36,305 --> 01:24:38,428
You don't ever change, do you, Dianne?

825
01:24:38,557 --> 01:24:41,226
Goddamn right I don't. Why should I?

826
01:24:42,352 --> 01:24:44,641
I was just commenting
on how good you look.

827
01:24:44,771 --> 01:24:48,815
- Yeah? I'll bet.
- Hey, how about a cup of tea?

828
01:24:48,941 --> 01:24:50,850
- Yeah.
- Yeah?

829
01:24:52,028 --> 01:24:55,112
So, how's that methadone
thing workin' out?

830
01:24:56,615 --> 01:24:58,109
So-so.

831
01:24:58,242 --> 01:25:03,698
- I got a job. Did I tell you that?
- No shit! Where are you working?

832
01:25:03,830 --> 01:25:04,779
Oh,

833
01:25:04,914 --> 01:25:06,954
just a machine shop over on Western.

834
01:25:07,083 --> 01:25:09,870
Yeah? What do you do there?

835
01:25:10,920 --> 01:25:13,589
I, uh... I drill holes.

836
01:25:14,173 --> 01:25:16,000
- Drill holes?
- Yeah.

837
01:25:16,133 --> 01:25:20,878
I drill... I drill these holes
that, uh, bolts fit into.

838
01:25:21,763 --> 01:25:24,337
Yeah? How do you like it?

839
01:25:24,474 --> 01:25:28,472
I'll tell you the truth. It's kind of
a drag, but it pays the rent.

840
01:25:32,982 --> 01:25:36,185
Then you're really serious.
You're gonna go on with this thing.

841
01:25:37,194 --> 01:25:38,569
Yeah.

842
01:25:41,240 --> 01:25:44,193
Dianne, why don't you take
your coat off and stay awhile?

843
01:25:44,326 --> 01:25:47,944
I can't. I got people
waiting for me out in the car.

844
01:25:48,079 --> 01:25:50,285
I just came to see how you was doing.

845
01:25:53,376 --> 01:25:54,704
Here.

846
01:25:55,503 --> 01:25:57,791
That's from Rick and the rest of us.

847
01:25:58,047 --> 01:26:01,498
We kind of thought you might
need a taste once in a while.

848
01:26:06,847 --> 01:26:09,598
What happened? What made you
turn around that day?

849
01:26:09,724 --> 01:26:12,641
Was it me? Did I do something wrong?

850
01:26:12,894 --> 01:26:15,349
No, babe. It wasn't you.

851
01:26:16,272 --> 01:26:20,186
It was Nadine's death and the hex
she threw on us with that hat.

852
01:26:20,818 --> 01:26:25,526
Then I panicked when I looked out to the
parking lot and I saw all those cop cars.

853
01:26:25,656 --> 01:26:30,613
I knew I was dead. So I started coppin'
deuces. I prayed like I'd never prayed.

854
01:26:30,744 --> 01:26:36,034
I said "God, Son, Devil, whoever you are
up there, please have pity on me."

855
01:26:36,165 --> 01:26:40,578
"Please let me get this poor girl's body
out of this hotel room and into the ground

856
01:26:40,711 --> 01:26:42,917
so I don't have to spend
my life in prison."

857
01:26:43,047 --> 01:26:48,337
"And, God, if you'll do that for me, I'll
show you my appreciation by goin' home,

858
01:26:49,427 --> 01:26:53,507
gettin' on the methadone programme,
gettin' a job and livin' a virtuous life."

859
01:26:56,684 --> 01:26:58,760
We got out,

860
01:26:58,894 --> 01:27:01,979
and I promised, so here I am.

861
01:27:03,315 --> 01:27:05,391
Are you gonna stick with it for ever?

862
01:27:08,570 --> 01:27:10,609
Well...

863
01:27:11,489 --> 01:27:16,732
You know, Dianne, for all the boredom the
straight life brings, it's not that bad.

864
01:27:16,869 --> 01:27:19,787
I mean, even this crummy
little room ain't so bad.

865
01:27:19,914 --> 01:27:22,156
I mean, I actually wake up some mornings

866
01:27:22,291 --> 01:27:25,874
and I feel like something good's
gonna happen today. You know?

867
01:27:27,337 --> 01:27:31,169
I'm a regular guy. I got my regular job.
I got my regular room.

868
01:27:34,177 --> 01:27:36,632
And now I got you.

869
01:27:39,390 --> 01:27:41,015
You're crazy, Bob.

870
01:27:41,892 --> 01:27:43,600
You're really crazy.

871
01:27:49,483 --> 01:27:51,855
Dianne, why don't you go downstairs

872
01:27:51,985 --> 01:27:56,196
and tell your friends that you're
gonna spend the night, come back,

873
01:27:56,322 --> 01:27:58,647
and bed down with me for a little while?

874
01:27:58,950 --> 01:28:01,156
I'd like to, Bob.

875
01:28:01,285 --> 01:28:03,574
But I got another old man now.

876
01:28:04,872 --> 01:28:08,952
I'm... I'm Rick's old lady now.
Ain't that a gas? I work for Rick.

877
01:28:09,668 --> 01:28:14,495
There we were, teaching that brat
to steal, and now I'm on his crew.

878
01:28:15,382 --> 01:28:18,299
Things sure can get
screwed around, can't they?

879
01:28:19,510 --> 01:28:20,708
Yeah.

880
01:28:20,845 --> 01:28:22,968
And, Bob, you know me.

881
01:28:23,097 --> 01:28:26,680
I might have been a lot of things,
but I never was a tramp.

882
01:28:52,916 --> 01:28:55,454
Bob, I gotta go.

883
01:29:17,272 --> 01:29:19,311
Hey, Dianne?

884
01:29:21,568 --> 01:29:23,726
It's really good to see you.

885
01:29:23,861 --> 01:29:25,901
I mean, you look really good.

886
01:29:28,824 --> 01:29:31,695
I wish I could win you back.

887
01:31:20,344 --> 01:31:23,214
- Who is it?
- Tom, it's Bob. Open the door.

888
01:31:26,433 --> 01:31:28,924
- Hey, what's this?
- It's a gift.

889
01:31:29,060 --> 01:31:32,227
I won't be needing it. I got
my new programme down so...

890
01:31:32,355 --> 01:31:34,762
- A gift. Wow.
- Knock yourself out.

891
01:31:34,899 --> 01:31:37,437
- Mmmm...
- I don't know what's in there.

892
01:31:37,568 --> 01:31:40,652
Let's just see what's in there.

893
01:31:46,535 --> 01:31:49,204
God bless you, my son.
May you go to heaven.

894
01:31:50,955 --> 01:31:52,236
Now...

895
01:31:52,373 --> 01:31:54,449
Oh, yeah. This...

896
01:31:55,167 --> 01:31:58,667
This is for squares. Never touch the stuff.

897
01:31:59,838 --> 01:32:01,878
But this...

898
01:32:05,218 --> 01:32:08,172
A hundred sixteenths of Dilaudid.

899
01:32:11,307 --> 01:32:15,008
This should earn you an indulgence.

900
01:32:34,037 --> 01:32:35,863
Where's it at, Bob?

901
01:32:37,665 --> 01:32:40,203
- What do you want?
- We want your dope.

902
01:32:40,334 --> 01:32:43,454
You think if I had dope
I'd be sittin' in this flea trap?

903
01:32:43,587 --> 01:32:47,287
I'm on a methadone programme. You
come around for dope? That's a laugh.

904
01:32:47,424 --> 01:32:50,378
Shut up. I ain't fucking, man.

905
01:32:50,510 --> 01:32:54,804
You want it the hard way and we're just
the guys who are gonna give it to you.

906
01:32:54,931 --> 01:32:57,173
Is that you, David?

907
01:32:58,601 --> 01:33:01,637
You listen to me, you little punk.
I'm goin' straight, man.

908
01:33:01,771 --> 01:33:04,807
I ain't fuckin' bullshitting you.
I'm goin' straight.

909
01:33:04,940 --> 01:33:07,561
You oughta try it sometime.
It's good for the soul.

910
01:33:07,693 --> 01:33:09,685
Fuckin' liar!

911
01:33:09,820 --> 01:33:13,271
Where is it, Bob? We know
this is all a scam you're playing.

912
01:33:13,406 --> 01:33:16,075
Where is it? Where the fuck is it?

913
01:33:29,171 --> 01:33:33,120
<i>Nothing is more life-affirming than
getting the shit kicked out of you.</i>

914
01:33:33,258 --> 01:33:36,128
<i>I knew it in my heart.
You can buck the system,</i>

915
01:33:36,261 --> 01:33:40,590
<i>but you can't buck the dark forces
that lie hidden beneath the surface.</i>

916
01:33:40,723 --> 01:33:43,392
<i>The ones some people
call superstitions.</i>

917
01:33:44,852 --> 01:33:46,595
<i>Howling banshees.</i>

918
01:33:46,729 --> 01:33:48,223
<i>Black cats.</i>

919
01:33:48,355 --> 01:33:50,182
<i>Hats on beds.</i>

920
01:33:50,315 --> 01:33:52,438
<i>Dogs and the evil eye.</i>

